}

* + table td {
    border-style:dashed;
}
</style>
<table>
    <tr>
        <th>name</th>
        <th>value</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>url</td>
        <td>the url of the media<br></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>file</td>
        <td>the path of the media file<br></td>
    </tr>
</table>
</div>


<h5>A real world example</h5>

<p><div class='bogus-wrapper'><notextile><figure class='code'> <div class="highlight"><table><tr><td class="gutter"><pre class="line-numbers"><span class='line-number'>1</span>
</pre></td><td class='code'><pre><code class='bash'><span class='line'>open -a /Applications/MPlayerX.app --args -file /Movies/myfavorite.mp4 -volume 50 -StartByFullScreen YES
</span></code></pre></td></tr></table></div></figure></notextile></div></p>

<ul>
<li><h3>For AppleScript</h3></li>
</ul>


<p>MPlayerX just started to support AppleScript in 1.0.17, its implementation still stays in primary status.</p>

<p>Usually you could use <em>AppleScript Editor</em> to look up all the functions provided by MPlayerX, for geeks, the source code is <a href="https://github.com/niltsh/MPlayerX/blob/sparkle/MPlayerX/MPlayerXScript.sdef">here</a>.</p>
